    title: 'The Economics of Biodiversity',
    text: 'Biodiversity — the variety of life at genetic, species, and ecosystem levels — has long been framed primarily as an environmental concern. Increasingly, however, economists and policymakers are recognising it as a fundamental economic asset. The Dasgupta Review, commissioned by the UK government and published in 2021, argued that nature constitutes a form of capital — "natural capital" — upon which all human economies ultimately depend, and that its ongoing degradation represents a profound market failure.\n\nEcosystem services, the benefits that functioning ecosystems provide to human societies, include pollination of crops, purification of water, regulation of climate, and protection of coastlines from flooding. Estimates of the annual economic value of these services run into the tens of trillions of dollars globally, though such figures are inherently difficult to calculate and contested among economists. What is not contested is that many of these services are provided for free by nature and are therefore invisible to conventional market accounting.\n\nThe economic case for biodiversity conservation rests on several arguments. First, the precautionary principle: given uncertainty about which species perform critical ecological functions, losing any species carries a risk of undermining systems we depend upon. Second, the pharmaceutical argument: a significant proportion of modern medicines derive from natural compounds, and undiscovered species may hold keys to future treatments. Third, resilience: diverse ecosystems are more stable and recover more readily from disturbances than simplified ones.\n\nCritics of economic valuation argue that placing monetary values on nature risks commodifying it in ways that ultimately enable rather than prevent its destruction — if a wetland can be "offset" by a payment, the incentive to preserve it in situ is weakened. This tension between valuation as a tool for conservation and valuation as a justification for exploitation remains unresolved in both policy and academic debate.',
