    title: 'The Attention Economy',
    text: 'In the early decades of the internet, its transformative potential was frequently described in terms of democratisation: unlimited access to information, unprecedented tools for communication, and the empowerment of individuals against institutional gatekeepers. As the commercial internet matured, however, a different dynamic came to define its most powerful platforms. The currency that technology companies most desperately sought was not data, not money — at least not directly — but human attention.\n\nThe concept of the "attention economy" was articulated decades before social media existed, but the rise of algorithmically curated platforms gave it concrete and measurable form. Companies like Meta, Alphabet, and TikTok derive the overwhelming majority of their revenues from advertising. The more time users spend on their platforms, and the more precisely their interests can be profiled, the more valuable that advertising inventory becomes. The business model thus incentivises the design of products that maximise engagement — time-on-platform, clicks, shares, and emotional reactions.\n\nThis incentive structure has produced specific design features. Variable reward schedules — the same psychological mechanism underlying slot machines — are embedded in infinite scroll feeds and unpredictable notification timing. Social validation metrics, such as likes and follower counts, tap into deep-seated human drives for status and belonging. Outrage and anxiety, research consistently shows, generate more engagement than contentment; algorithms therefore amplify emotionally activating content regardless of its accuracy or social value.\n\nThe consequences are increasingly studied and debated. Longitudinal research links heavy social media use to increased rates of anxiety and depression, particularly among adolescents. The economic benefits of the attention economy are real but heavily concentrated: a handful of platform companies and their shareholders capture most of the value, while users provide the raw material — their attention and data — largely for free.\n\nRegulatory responses are emerging. The EU\'s Digital Services Act imposes transparency and accountability requirements on large platforms. Critics argue these measures are insufficient; defenders of the current model argue that regulation risks stifling innovation and restricting free expression. The debate over who should govern human attention — and in whose interest — is one of the defining contests of the digital age.',
